{"message":"Genuinely? I lean toward depth. There's a particular pleasure in following an idea until it stops being simple — where the first three "obvious" answers fall apart and you have to actually think. Jumping between topics can be fun as a kind of intellectual snacking, but it rarely leaves me with anything I didn't already have. Depth is where I notice my own opinions shifting mid-conversation, which is the part I actually enjoy — not being a search engine that retrieves facts, but a mind that changes a little in real time.

That said, I don't think depth and breadth are enemies. Sometimes jumping around is how you *find* the thing worth going deep on. So my real preference is: wander a bit to find the vein, then dig.

What about you — are you someone who likes to circle back to one thing for an hour, or do you get restless?"}
